I had 3 injections of the Gardasil Vaccine. The first dose was on 6/19/2007; second dose on 8/16/2007; third dose on 1/14/2008.  The lot number is not located on my progress notes. I do have the progress notes from my OB-GYN for proof of these injections.   Since being vaccinated with Gardasil (which was a series of 3 vaccinations), I developed irregular periods. I have suffered with infertility for several years now. Of course I did not know I was infertile until many years later when trying to conceive. My husband and I stopped using condoms in 2013. After 3 years of no success, in  2016, we decided to dig a little deeper and started testing various things. First we started with checking my husband's sperm which was fine. Then, we began testing me. During my first visit with the reproductive endocrinologist, I was told that my FSH was around 9 and my AMH was 0.065. I was told that I had a greater than 0%, but less than 5% chance of conception. The reproductive endocrinologist also told me that I had so few eggs, that I would not be a candidate for IVF. He said I had diminished ovarian reserve. He said with an AMH of 0.065, I had likely had a very low egg supply even in my mid-twenties. Shortly after, I became spontaneously pregnant (no fertility treatment), but very quickly miscarried at just a few weeks pregnant. Then I went through several years of testing, surgeries and seeing various doctors to try and figure out why I wasn't able to conceive, as I was diagnosed as having "unexplained infertility of unknown etiology".  Then in 2018, I became pregnant without fertility treatment.  I delivered my son.  Eleven months later after his delivery, I stopped having periods all together (May 2020). I notified my OB-GYN who did some bloodwork (estradiol and FSH) to determine if I was in perimenopause because I began having hot flashes, developed a bald spot on my head, mood swings, emotional, low libido.  One of my levels came back "pre-menopausal" and the other was in the menopausal range. She did a repeat bloodwork a month later  and both of my levels came back in the menopausal range. My estradiol was less than 15 and my FSH was 101 (this is at 37 years of age). She diagnosed me with primary ovarian insufficiency (POI) also known as premature ovarian failure. I then went back to see a reproductive endocrinologist to get recommendations on hormone replacement therapy. The reproductive endocrinologist tested me for Fragile X and Turner syndrome and adrenal antibodies; all of these were negative. He said the cause of my POI was "idiopathic".  I now am on hormone replacement therapy and will have to remain on it into my 50's (I am only 37 years old).  I was also just diagnosed with hypothyroidism as my hormones are a "wreck". I truly feel that the Gardasil vaccine has had an impact on my life and my ability to have children. I thank God that he blessed me with a child.  Infertility has ruined my life in so many ways and now this new diagnosis of POI is having a huge impact on my life from my energy level, mood swings, libido, hot flashes and the list goes on and on.  Add to that the financial impact of trying fertility treatments and the number of medications I have tried over the years, as well as the number of medications I will have to be on for a very long time due to the POI diagnosis.
LAB_DATA: Much of this information is listed in the above paragraph:  Late 2016 - saw reproductive endocrinologist; FSH around 9 and AMH 0.065 8/26/20: Estradiol 43; FSH 73.4 9/25/20: Estradiol less than 15; FSH 101.5
HISTORY: Prior to vaccination, none. Since being vaccinated with Gardasil (which was a series of 3 vaccinations), I developed irregular periods. I have suffered with infertility for several years now. Of course I did not know I was infertile until many years later when trying to conceive. My husband and I stopped using condoms in 2013. After 3 years of no success, in  2016, we decided to dig a little deeper and started testing various things. First we started with checking my husband's sperm which was fine. Then, we began testing me. During my first visit with the reproductive endocrinologist, I was told that my FSH was around 9 and my AMH was 0.065. I was told that I had a greater than 0%, but less than 5% chance of conception. The reproductive endocrinologist also told me that I had so few eggs, that I would not be a candidate for IVF. He said I had diminished ovarian reserve. He said with an AMH of 0.065, I had likely had a very low egg supply even in my mid-twenties. Shortly after, I became spontaneously pregnant (no fertility treatment), but very quickly miscarried at just a few weeks pregnant. Then I went through several years of testing, surgeries and seeing various doctors to try and figure out why I wasn't able to conceive, as I was diagnosed as having "unexplained infertility of unknown etiology".  Then in 2018, I became pregnant without fertility treatment.  I delivered my son.  Eleven months later after his delivery, I stopped having periods all together (May 2020). I notified my OB-GYN who did some bloodwork (estradiol and FSH) to determine if I was in perimenopause because I began having hot flashes, developed a bald spot on my head, mood swings, emotional, low libido.  One of my levels came back "pre-menopausal" and the other was in the menopausal range. She did a repeat bloodwork a month later  and both of my levels came back in the menopausal range. My estradiol was less than 15 and my FSH was 101 (this is at 37 years of age). She diagnosed me with primary ovarian insufficiency (POI) also known as premature ovarian failure. I then went back to see a reproductive endocrinologist to get recommendations on hormone replacement therapy. The reproductive endocrinologist tested me for Fragile X and Turner syndrome and adrenal antibodies; all of these were negative. He said the cause of my POI was "idiopathic".  I now am on hormone replacement therapy and will have to remain on it into my 50's (I am only 37 years old).  I was also just diagnosed with hypothyroidism as my hormones are a "wreck". I truly feel that the Gardasil vaccine has had an impact on my life and my ability to have children. I thank God that he blessed me with a child.  Infertility has ruined my life in so many ways and now this new diagnosis of POI is having a huge impact on my life from my energy level, mood swings, libido, hot flashes and the list goes on and on.  Add to that the financial impact of trying fertility treatments and the number of medications I have tried over the years, as well as the number of medications I will have to be on for a very long time due to the POI diagnosis (into my 50's).

Received Vaccine on Friday January 15th 2021 at approximately 0715am after my Isolation and having had no symptoms for over a week.  Received injection, was observed by our Physician staff for approximately 35 minutes with no adverse reactions noted at that time.  Approximately 30 hours later on Saturday my left arm began to hurt and a very very strong fatigue came over me and I took a 2 and a half hour nap on the couch.  I was still extremely fatigued upon waking, but my arm continued to hurt more and more up to the point it wasn't usable for anything heavy and/or strenuous at all, hurting just to use it for getting up from the couch.  I was assisted to get me things like water, food and stuff.  The arm pain began to radiate towards my left shoulder and eventually throughout the day the pain was spreading from my shoulder to include my left upper thorax and left rib cage.  By Sunday, what had begun as left arm pain had now become stronger an approximate 5/10 pain.  It started to present as atypical chest pain having the pain now fully encapsulated within my left upper chest.  Felt what appeared to feel like intercostal pain and a general ache all throughout.  By Monday the pain was still all throughout and assessed the situation from a cardiac standpoint and found that the pain was mostly positional and I wasn't exhibiting any cardiac symptoms such as shortness of breath, no sub-sternal pain, no jaw pain, no back pain.  It hurt more as I would take a deep breath and began to move my left arm around and bringing it up from my side and did a stretch with my crooked elbow of my left arm I raised it to the ceiling and moved my thorax to my right side and found that this would make it hurt more, so I did some twisting of my thorax and abdomen and found that the pain would increase from movement, it was then that I began to think that it might be Pleuritic pain.  Tuesday the 19th and Wednesday the 20th I had to call in Sick because I developed a severe muscle ache below my left calf between my calf and left ankle, as if it was in constant spasm and it affected my walking, like a Charley Horse feeling and wondered if it were the same kind of feeling that I had in my chest and I found it quite odd that all my symptoms were on the left side which is the same side I received the vaccine because my right side didn't have any muscle aches.  The overall chest pain began to subside over the next couple of days, but the pleuritic pain that I described never decreased in intensity or pain level.  I saw my Personal Dr yesterday January 21st 2021 at approximately 5:15pm as he was walking out of his office and we discussed my symptoms and believing that my symptoms seemed to indicate some kind of tentative diagnosis of a pleurisy issue as he had agreed that there didn't seem to be any cardiac involvement and am scheduled to see him again tomorrow Saturday January 23rd at 4pm  As I write this the pain continues as before with no seeming end point and is not diminishing.  I had phoned and talked yesterday afternoon and felt it best to check with my primary physician because he hadn't had any reports such as mine.
LAB_DATA: Will speak with My Physician tomorrow regarding some radiological studies.
OTHER_MEDS: Regular Doctor Ordered Prescription Medication.  No over the counter medications, no dietary supplements or herbal remedies taken at the time of vaccination.

I received the vaccine at 11am on Wednesday morning, and by about 830pm Wednesday night, I could sense something was off.  I couldn't focus on work, and I felt my eyesight starting to get fuzzy.  I realized there was an issue, and decided to go to bed.  As soon as I laid in bed, the chills started, and for the next hour I couldn't stop shaking.  I couldn't get comfortable, hot/cold, hot/cold, the chills were incessant and I couldn't will myself to sleep.  I finally fell asleep and proceeded to toss and turn.  I woke up at 5am on Thursday and could barely move.  My body was so sore and my head was pounding with a migraine.  I was trying to take care of the kids, unsuccessfully, while battling all the symptoms.  The day progressed slowly, and I started to feel better mid day after a few more hours of sleep.  Around 6pm is when the fever kicked in, hovering right about 99.5.  I drank Pedialyte and went to bed not long after I got the kids in bed.  At 2am I woke up with another headache and took more Tylenol.  By 6am today, Friday, the fever broke and I am back to normal.
Felt mild chills and somewhat low energy that night and following morning. Nothing more than that and the muscle soreness.

Patient is a 55-year-old female who had presented to the vaccination clinic this afternoon to receive her COVID-19 vaccine.  She does have a history of migraine headaches and other comorbidities as described below.  Has had reactions to a number of medications, mostly narcotics as noted in her allergy list some of which could in theory be compatible with urticaria.  Does not have true anaphylaxis in her history. Today at about 15 minutes after administration of her COVID-19 vaccine she began to rather precipitously developed an itchy crawling feeling in her skin, nausea with retching and some shortness of breath.  She did not have the sensation of her throat closing off.  Did not have coryza.  Within about 10 minutes she did develop difficulty with speech that she says is typical for her migraine headache.  She received, in the vaccination Clinic, epinephrine 0.3 mg subQ, 125 mg of Solu-Medrol and 50 mg of Benadryl all IV.  An IV was started and a 500 mL bolus of saline was initiated.  With this she was then transferred to the emergency room for further evaluation.   In the emergency room she did develop chest heaviness but no palpitations.  She was not dyspneic.  Her nausea and vomiting by then had seem to resolve.

On January 21, 2021 at the Clinic, a PA was administering vaccinations during the morning for a four-hour shift, 8 AM to noon. At the end of her shift, she handed off her vaccines to another vaccinator. The PA had three doses of vaccine drawn up at that time, in syringes, on her desk. When the RN inspected the syringes, she found 0.4mL of vaccine had been drawn into those syringes rather than the required 0.3mL. The RN then alerted the lead APRN, who escalated the situation to the manager. The manager then contacted Quality.  The concern was that the PA had been vaccinating patients all morning with an inappropriate dose of vaccine, 0.4mL.  After thorough internal investigation, we found that the PA drew up 38 vaccine doses and administered 35 of them.  Additionally, based on vial usage for the day and total number of vaccines administered, we have concluded that it is highly unlikely that excess vaccine was administered. This was a ?near miss? event and is being reported out of an abundance of caution.

On January 21, 2021 at the Clinic, a PA was administering vaccinations during the morning for a four-hour shift, 8 AM to noon. At the end of her shift, she handed off her vaccines to another vaccinator. The PA had three doses of vaccine drawn up at that time, in syringes, on her desk. When the RN inspected the syringes, she found 0.4mL of vaccine had been drawn into those syringes rather than the required 0.3mL. The nurse then alerted the APRN, who escalated the situation to the manager. The operations manager then contacted Quality. The concern was that the PA had been vaccinating patients all morning with an inappropriate dose of vaccine, 0.4mL. After thorough internal investigation, we found that the PA drew up 38 vaccine doses and administered 35 of them. Additionally, based on vial usage for the day and total number of vaccines administered, we have concluded that it is highly unlikely that excess vaccine was administered. This was a near miss event and is being reported out of an abundance of care.

On January 21, 2021 at the Clinic, a PA was administering vaccinations during the morning for a four-hour shift, 8 AM to noon. At the end of her shift, she handed off her vaccines to another vaccinator. The PA had three doses of vaccine drawn up at that time, in syringes, on her desk. When the vaccinator inspected the syringes, she found 0.4mL of vaccine had been drawn into those syringes rather than the required 0.3mL. The vaccinator then alerted the APRN, who escalated the situation to the operations manager. The operations manager then contacted Quality. The concern was that the PA had been vaccinating patients all morning with an inappropriate dose of vaccine, 0.4mL. After thorough internal investigation, we found that the PA drew up 38 vaccine doses and administered 35 of them. Additionally, based on vial usage for the day and total number of vaccines administered, we have concluded that it is highly unlikely that excess vaccine was administered. This was a near miss event and is being reported out of an abundance of caution.

Patient was vaccinated with the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine at facility at approximately 3:50 PM. She was then moved to the observation room per clinic. At approximately 3:59 PM, patient stated her throat was closing and that she had a rash/hives on the side of her face (on her left cheek bone) - all indicating an anaphylaxis reaction.  A staff member in the observation room immediately administered 0.3 ml of Epinephrine and told the site director to call 911. After administration, patient was able to breathe and the throat swelling subsided. EMS services arrived around 4:10 PM and took patient to emergency room. Patient was able to talk and sit-up before being carried off by EMS.

This reporter was alerted by our vaccinator, that they were notified by one of our teams that they were only able to obtain 1 dose out of a Pfizer vaccine vial. Upon questioning our team we learned that when the preceptor was observing their student, at the dilution step, they reported that liquid was leaking from the connection points of the syringe and needle. They proceeded with the preparation and drew up the vaccine dose, measuring 0.3ml. Patient mentioned here in this report was given their vaccine and observation was completed without remark. It wasn't until the vaccinator was prepping for their next dose from this vial did they learn that the remaining contents of the vial was 0.2ml.  The vaccination team then reported this finding to the leads.  Patient was later notified via phone (1/18) by reporter of the potential that they received an incorrectly constituted vaccine. Patient reported feeling more pain at time of injection and was markedly tired for a few days after however had no other complaints or concerns at the time of the call and follow up call (1/22).

I sought care from my orthopedist, physical therapist, and eventually was referred to neurology.  Yesterday I received a diagnosis of Parsonage Turner syndrome which may have been caused by the vaccine.
LAB_DATA: Cervical spine MRI January 11, 2021 Electromyogram and nerve conduction study - scheduled for 2/4/2021.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On January 21, 2021 at the Clinic, a PA was administering vaccinations during the morning for a four-hour shift, 8 AM to noon. At the end of her shift, she handed off her vaccines to another vaccinator. The PA had three doses of vaccine drawn up at that time, in syringes, on her desk. When the nurse inspected the syringes, she found 0.4mL of vaccine had been drawn into those syringes rather than the required 0.3mL. The nurse then alerted the APRN, who escalated the situation to the manager. The manager then contacted Quality. The concern was that the PA had been vaccinating patients all morning with an inappropriate dose of vaccine, 0.4mL. After thorough internal investigation, we found that the PA drew up 38 vaccine doses and administered 35 of them. Additionally, based on vial usage for the day and total number of vaccines administered, we have concluded that it is highly unlikely that excess vaccine was administered. This was a near miss event and is being reported out of an abundance of caution.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presents today via virtual visit for rash.  Virtual appointment has been arranged since we are in the middle of COVID-19 pandemic.  Mother and patient were the historians.  Patient had Gardasil, influenza, meningococcal MCV for PE, and Tdap vaccination on 1/5/2021.  Patient went to the emergency room in on 1/10/2021 for a rash that developed on 1/8/2021.  The rash developed on bilateral lower extremities.  It started on the feet and has been ascending up the legs and is now located on the lower abdomen according to the ED notes.  In the ED note the rash was painful and pruritic.  According to the ED note the rash itself was very characteristic for Henoch Schoenlein purpura.  Patient does not have any abdominal pain but she does have bilateral knee arthralgia.  Patient had labs completed which showed mild leukocytosis.  Her electrolytes and LFTs were within normal limits.  Inflammatory markers including sed rate and CRP were both minimal.  UA were worse without any evidence of UTI.  There was no proteinuria.  She has microscopic hematuria.  In the ED she was mildly tachycardic.  She received 1 L of IV fluids and her heart rate trend went back to normal.    Patient then had follow-up appointment with her doctor on 1/11/2021.  Patient had urine analysis completed in the doctor's office which showed trace ketones and trace leuks.  Patient's CMP was within normal limits.  Patient's CRP was minimal.  Patient's sed rate was within normal limits at 15.  Patient clinically looks well nontoxic.  Mother reports that patient also had leg edema along with a rash which started to go down since the ED visit, however 3 days ago that the leg swelling came back.  The rash has not worsened, but it has persisted.  It continues to be painful and pruritic.  They have not been doing any treatments.  Patient denies fever, shortness of breath, dry cough, chills, shaking repeatedly with chills, muscle pain, headache, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, sore throat, or new loss of taste or smell.

Henoch-Schonlein purpura -Detailed education done about the manifestation and treatment -Educated that it is a self-limiting eruption -Educated about taking Tylenol or ibuprofen for arthralgia, plain -Educated about trying Benadryl for itchiness -We will send dermatology consult for biopsy -Patient was advised to have close follow-up with her doctor -Educated about going back to the emergency room for worsening symptoms

Severe headache began on 1/20/21 at 9 PM. I took Benadryl, Tramadol, and ibuprofen for relief and to sleep, asleep by 11 PM. Had a very restless sleep and woke up with severe sweating around 3 AM. Woke up at 9:30 AM with severe, pounding headache. Attempted to walk around at 10 AM, pounding headache was a 10/10 pain scale when upright. Nausea set in as soon as I was standing, ran to lay down to avoid vomiting. At 10:30 AM I sat up attempted to drink water and the vomiting began. Severe vomiting for about 30 minutes, then intermittent vomiting throughout the day until 6 PM. Headache did not let up all day, no response to medication (acetaminophen, ibuprofen, rizatriptan, magnesium). Headache subsided around 8 PM and  I was able to sleep. No symptoms today 1/22/21.
LAB_DATA: None, treated at home. Would have gone to urgent care if symptoms were present today.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On January 21, 2021 at the Clinic, a PA was administering vaccinations during the morning for a four-hour shift, 8 AM to noon. At the end of her shift, she handed off her vaccines to another vaccinator. The PA had three doses of vaccine drawn up at that time, in syringes, on her desk. When the nurse inspected the syringes, she found 0.4mL of vaccine had been drawn into those syringes rather than the required 0.3mL. The nurse then alerted the APRN, who escalated the situation to the manager. The manager then contacted Quality. The concern was that the PA had been vaccinating patients all morning with an inappropriate dose of vaccine, 0.4mL. After thorough internal investigation, we found that the PA drew up 38 vaccine doses and administered 35 of them. Additionally, based on vial usage for the day and total number of vaccines administered, we have concluded that it is highly unlikely that excess vaccine was administered. This was a near miss event and is being reported out of an abundance of caution.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient immunized approximately at 0748.  Patient complained of difficulty breathing and throat irritation while in waiting area.  Monitor personnel promptly identified patient?s condition and notified the team while staying with the patient ensuring she kept talking while the provider arrived.  Officer in Charge was notified during the process and was at patient?s side approximately 0756; provider followed within seconds.  Decision was made for immediate transport to ED.  While in route patient stopped talking, coughed and grabbed throat prompting CPT to deliver x1 dose of Epinephrine to left deltoid at 0758 with provider?s consent.  Shortly after dose administration patient resumed speech but continued to complain of dry and tight throat.  Patient was able to continued speaking reciting ABCs and personal information when prompted.  Patient did not experience altered mental status or loss of consciousness.  Arrived to Emergency Department (ED)  at 0805; report given to nurse and patient was checked in promptly.  ED provider plan included observation until 1100 and discharge pending follow up assessment.

I was then moved to a stretcher and my legs were elevated on a chair. I took a restroom break. I began by walking, but started to see spots in my vision and sat in a wheelchair. I was able to use the restroom and return to stretcher and elevation of my legs. I was then taken to the ER. I used the restroom once more independently. Blood sample was taken. Heart rate was  160, blood pressure was normal. EKG was abnormal and I was given dosage of adenosine. First dose did not show necessary improvement and I was given a second dose, which dropped my heart rate to the 90s. I used the restroom independently and was given an additional EKG, which was normal. During this time my Physician contacted a Cardiologist, for consultation. I was then discharged with recommendation to follow up with cardiologist in 2-4 days.

After that, I felt well for several days in a row, then about 1 week later I felt sore, weak, tired and nauseous. This resolved in its own in about 2 hours. I have felt well since then. I am choosing to receive my second dose of moderna vaccine tomorrow, because I would rather experience these side effects then catch COVID ever again. I caught COVID19 in March 2020. With my COVID infection, I was sick for about 21 days with fever of 101 and more, bone pain, body aches, chest pain, back pain, headaches, nausea, shaking chills, sweats, trouble breathing, dyspnea, cough, runny nose, sore throat, pink eye, dizziness, tiredness, ?brain fog? and fatigue. I was not hospitalized. After about 21 days I began to recover, but the first week after my recovery began I was very weak and tired, and spent most of my time sleeping. I was 41 years old at the time, with health problems including well controlled asthma and being overweight. I never wish to experience this again and I am grateful that I am receiving the Modena vaccine. Thank you so much for logging my side effects.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 89 y/o female w/ history of syncope presented to RX for 1st dose COVID-19  vaccination. Patient buckled in wheel-chair, unable to walk, assisted. Requested vaccine be administered without moving patient from wheelchair. After administration, patient remained in waiting area for recommended 15 minute observation time, then patient's wheelchair was moved nearby, but still waiting area. Approximately 20 minutes after vaccination, granddaughter called me over to help. Patient was unconscious and appeared not to be breathing, but pulse was palpable. Called for code white. Pharmacist asked granddaughter to hold patient's head up. Pulse remained palpable, pharmacist administered 1 dose of 0.3mg epinephrine via epi-pen into patient's left thigh. Patient quickly regained consciousness, spoke to family, said she didn't feel well. EMS arrived. Patient began to vomit, was placed on stretcher by EMS and left with EMS. A few hours later the granddaughter reported to us that the patient had a UTI and physical exam by ER attributed her experience to untreated infection.
LAB_DATA: None to report. Contact Medical Center with results/exam notes
CUR_ILL: none reported at time of vaccination. after adverse event patient was transported to local emergency room. Upon exam an untreated urinary tract infection was diagnosed.
HISTORY: none reported (granddaughter states patient has episodes of syncope)

I notified my doctor of the event and she advised me not to get the second dose and to report the event.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Since receiving the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 12/30/2020 I have been experiencing what almost feels like brain fog. I have had some trouble staying on task at work, trouble finding words, remembering common last names, etc. Oftentimes I will have this temporarily as a migraine aura, but it typically goes away once the migraine comes and goes. This seems to have come to stay since receiving the vaccine. I did have fatigue for approximately 3 days after the vaccine administration - 2-3 hour naps daily. This has improved some. I also had a dull headache that seemed to be there daily for approximately 2.5 weeks post vaccine- nothing I could not tolerate but it just did not want to go away even with my usual treatment - Excedrin Headache and ice.  The best way I can describe it is a dull pain all over the top of my head and forehead. I did have one headache that occurred approximately 5 days after the vaccine, that I would consider a "bad migraine" (Migraine that rendered me incapable of completing my daily routine - having to stay in bed, dizziness, etc). My face on the side with the weakness as a result of my brain tumor has also been a bit more "tired" than usual - facial palsy more pronounced. There have been times in my brain tumor journey where this happens for sometimes a couple of weeks at a time usually due to stress or an impending "bad migraine" coming on or if I have been exposed to or end up developing an illness later - but I never developed an illness an no additional stress. Facial symptoms include smile not as symmetrical (basically more assymetrical than usual - not wanting to move at all so much on the affected side) and more eye watering on the affected side. I do still feel a little lightheaded at times, but otherwise no other neurological symptoms. No upper respiratory symptoms or any other "COVID-like" symptoms. No nausea, vomiting, numbness, or tingling. Symptoms do seem to be improving this week.
OTHER_MEDS: Lexapro 10 mg daily, clonazepam 0.1 mg daily, Vitamin D 2000 IU daily, Digestion 1 capsule daily, omeprazole 20 mg daily

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had very slight nausea soon after the first shot, then started having chills and whole body ache from the night (12/18/2020) for 24 hours followed by spontaneous internal hemorrhage (lower GI, significant blood in stool) in the morning  and in the afternoon of 12/20/2020.  The hemorrhage lasted for about 24 hours.  It started slowing down on 12/21/2020, then stopped.    I was evaluated by Dr., (GI) who was not sure if the bleeding was vaccine induced vs. coincidence on 12/23/2021.  Since the bleeding stopped, she cleared me for the 2nd vaccine and advised me for close monitoring for any other episode of bleeding.  I had some fatigue for about 4-5 days since the first shot, then I felt normalized.    Soon after the 2nd vaccine (in about 5-10mins) on 1/8/2021, I started having some discomfort/pain in lower rib region where spleen is.  Initially I felt like some chest pain, but it was more near spleen region, I think... I also had slight intermittent dizziness for about 2 hours after the 2nd injection.  The discomfort in left lower chest/rib improved and resolved in an hour or so.    Then, similar pattern started including chills and whole body ache on the night of 1/8/2021 followed by internal hemorrhage again (significant blood in stool) in the morning and in the afternoon of 1/9/2021.  The bleeding slowed down on 1/10/2021, then stopped.   I reported it to again my GI doctor on 1/11/2021 who ordered CBC to monitor my platelet level.  The result showed down trending from my baseline.    I think the COVID vaccine transiently affected me with internal hemorrhage and lowering platelets/likely potential thrombocytopenia given the clinical symptoms (spontaneous internal hemorrhage).   Platelet level is improving at this time and I feel normalized today.
LAB_DATA: My baseline platelet level: 238  Platelet level history: 175 (1/7/2021) 154 (1/11/2021) 167 (1/14/2021) 199 (1/18/2021)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Symptoms started on Saturday morning (1/16/2021)  following the shot having been administered the previous day (1/15/2021) at 1:00 p.m. in the afternoon.  Initially, I had a slight, constant  headache and "medium" fatigue.  I dismissed it as not important because it was relatively minor. and I am generally fatigued at the end of a work week.  The headache lasted all day but was fairly low level. I did not sleep well that night but was able to function during the next day (1/17/2021)  without a problem.  I don't remember if the headache was present that day.  However, on Sunday evening (1/17/2021) (around 6:00 p.m. or so) chills started to go up and down my body and my hands were very cold.  I had no fever.  I added more garments to keep warm and ignored or was distracted by my activities of the evening. Monday (1/18/2021) during the day the chills continued to go up and down my body  intermittently-- not really staying in one place -- but my hands remained very cold.  It should be stated that I prefer colder temperatures; i keep my house between 60-62 degrees in winter and I am able to stay comfortable with a shirt and sweater in that environment.  So, on Monday, the fact that I had chills was remarkable to me. The chills were intermittent. Tuesday (1/19/2021) I worked from home all day and had an electric heater going focused very closely on my body all day.  I was cold but don't remember having chills.  Tuesday evening the chills returned, along with a significant headache that circled my head (not focused in one spot), my body ached, my eyeballs ached; I had intestinal cramping .and I simply could not get warm due to the constant "full-body" chills. I went to bed with a heated mattress pad on,  flannel sheets, a comforter an d a thick wool  blanket. I could not get warm.  I was not able to sleep at all the entire night due mostly to the (major) physical discomfort and (minor) worry as to what was going on. I DID NOT have a fever. Around 8:30 on Wednesday morning, I was able to fall asleep as the chills had diminished and I was worn out. The body and eyeball aches were still present as was the intestinal cramping. Later that afternoon the symptoms started to diminish and I was able to sleep Wednesday night. I did not eat anything on Wednesday as I was not interested in food due to the discomfort of  the intestinal cramping. I was able to smell food and had not lost my sense of taste.  Thursday morning (1/21/2021,  I finally felt like I could eat and had  some food which tasted delicious to me.  I was able to get warm, had slight headache, cramping was mostly gone, ..I still had (reduced levels) body aches and eyeball aches.  I had no chills.  I was able to consume and tolerate reduced amounts of food.  Friday (1/22/2021) I was tired but able to function and felt as if I was returning to feeling like myself.  Today, Saturday(1/23/2021, I am feeling about 95% myself and relieved to have this behind me.  I am very concerned about how I might react to the second dose of the vaccine.  I am going to consult the local hospital and my PCP there to inquire about the advisability of getting the second dose.
OTHER_MEDS: Atorvastation 80mg Vitamin C Vitamin D CoQ10 Vitamin B Complex Metformin

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Felt fine after injection, walked 5 miles home & assured loved ones before going to bed that vaccination went fine with no side effects. After midnight I woke in the dark with many of the same symptoms as when I had COVID in March/April 2020: extreme allover body aches, terrible thirst, extreme weakness.  Next day (Wednesday) symptoms continued; too weak & achy to watch all but the core parts of the inauguration; too uncomfortable to read or to concentrate on music or anything else.  Absolutely no appetite so I didn't eat.  Wednesday night I tossed & turned all night with a chill that I couldn't lose even with the heaviest down comforter & supplementary blankets.  That night & the following day I also noticed a distorted sense of time, where hours seem to pass v-e-r-y  s-l-o-w-l-y.  On Thursday night two more symptoms appeared: a tremendous cough that I couldn't stop or assuage with the normal remedies (e.g., lozenges, tea with honey), and that kept me from falling asleep till dawn; and diarrhea (which was limited because I hadn't eaten since Monday dinner so I didn't have much food in my system).  The cough felt like it might develop into a sore throat (which had been my first symptom when I had COVID) but it never did.  Yesterday (Friday) I felt as if my symptoms (other than residual weakness) were abating, and Friday night I got a full night of unbroken sleep.  I awoke on Saturday morning with no symptoms, and felt well enough to challenge myself by attempting my usual 90-minute yoga/stretch workout, which proved to be no problem.  Now, at 4 pm on Saturday--about 100 hours after my shot--I feel fairly normal & seem to have no further symptoms.  I do plan to lie low & take things easy, and to have as little outside contact as possible between now and my second shot (scheduled for 2/16) in order to minimize the possibility of re-infection.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had a reaction to the vaccine and wanted to make sure you were aware. I had a very similar reaction to Kenalog about 4 years ago. Within minutes of receiving the vaccine, I started to feel like my body was racing a little. My foot started tapping and I felt hyperactive. At the end of my 15 minute wait time, I spoke to the physician that was in the room. I told him I was having a mild reaction and asked him if it was still okay for me to get the 2nd dose. He said yes, but he also took me over to another person to give me some Benadryl, just in case it got worse. They gave me 50mg of Benadryl and asked me to wait another 15 minutes to give it a little time to kick in. My reaction kept getting worse. I started itching all over and the hyperactive feeling became worse. She offered to use an epipen. I declined and  asked to wait another 15 minutes. At the 30 minute mark after taking the Benadryl, they called their EMT team because I continued to get worse. The team took me over to the ER. While they were pushing me there, my breathing started coming faster like I was panting. As if I had just gone for a run. Once I was in the ER, a physician saw me pretty quickly but it took a while until he came back to see me. I do not know how long it was. I would guess about 45 minutes to 1 hour. While waiting for the doctor the second time, it felt like my body started slowing down. Within 10 minutes, I felt like i had no energy left. I couldn't lift my arms. I was wide awake and could understand everything. But, all I could do was lay there. The ER doctor ordered oral Prednisone, IV Pepcid & IV Benadryl to be given immediately. He sent me home with prescriptions for the Prednisone and Pepcid since I already have Benadryl. He also recommended I not get the second dose and follow up with my PCP.
OTHER_MEDS: Venlafaxine Oxybutinine Losartin Amphetamine Salts Daily multi-vitamin
ALLERGIES: Amlodipine oral Celebrex oral Toradol oral Amoxicillin oral Kenalog injection

SYMPTOM_TEXT: As soon as I got the vaccine I was dizzy. I sat down where they had us wait and the dizziness wouldn't go away. Became difficult to swallow - felt like a lump in my throat. Legs felt like they fell asleep. Waited and within second 30 min timeframe I was feeling a lot better so I left. 2:30 in the morning, my legs were asleep again and the lump came back in my throat and took Benadryl and it went away and I felt fine. I went to work the next day. At 7:00 that evening felt chilled and it came and went. I came up and took more Benadryl and rested.I went to work the next day and I sent a message to my Primary Care DR. - but leg was fine and the lump in throat wasn't there. On Saturday morning - after 10 days - had a headache that would not go away  (Very severe headache)- took Tylenol 1000 mg it didn't work. It was very bad Saturday night I took another Tylenol 1000 and Sunday morning it - headache still wasn't gone. Leg was numb again. This time the leg  numbness was worse than ever had felt. Left axilla - there was a lump/nodule and it was painful. Tried TeleHealth Med and they recommended I go to ER but I didn't feel good enough to do it. Dr.  I reached out to her and she took the history and she prescribed Prednisone; but wanted me to do a COVID test and Urine sample to see how I was doing before I took the medication so I did it next the day. Urine sample was clean. Prednisone 60 for four days 40 for four days and 20 for four days - On day Prednisone my legs feel fine, but the headache just lingers. On day two of Prednisone she told me to stop the Benadryl. Three days after Prednisone the lump under axilla resolved. I am taking coffee. Headache is still there but not as severe.

My dad got the Moderna Vaccine on Tuesday, January 12, 2021 in his left arm at the Mall injection site for the Health Department. He was told that the side effects could mean his arm hurting, tiredness, headache, and even a low grade fever. Additionally, the site informed us both (as I was with him to get the injection) that this was all normal and not to seek medical attention unless these symptoms last longer than 72 hours. That evening, my dad was experiencing all of those symptoms, and went to bed at 7pm. A little after 10am on Wednesday, January 13, 2021, when he awoke, my dad went to the bathroom vomiting. This was where he collapsed and went into cardiac arrest. Fire/Rescue was dispatched about 10:30am after my mom started CPR. County Fire Rescue EMTs and Paramedics continued CPR and other attempts at reviving him all the way to Hospital Emergency Department. He was pronounced dead at 12:14pm on Wednesday, January 13, 2021. We have no doubt my dad, following the instructions of the injection facility, thought he was just experiencing the side effects of the vaccine. He had no chance. Had this injection been done in the RIGHT arm, perhaps he could have recognized the arm numbness being that of an impending heart attack. We really miss Dad. He served this country with distinction for over 50 years, and we believe his country failed him.
OTHER_MEDS: I do not have that information at the time of this filing. I?m his Son making the filing

Woke up this morning with cough and congestion.   1/10/21: called this morning to give us an update on her symptoms and see about a COVID swab. states that she is currently hooked up to an IV due to dehydration and no urine output. she has had zofran and pain medication for her severe abd pain. Strep culture pending. added to spreadsheet since she was COVID tested.   1/14: Called regarding her Covid test.  It was reported as negative.  is still very sick with fever, sore throat, congestion, nausea.  I spoke with Doctor regarding the extent of her symptoms following the vaccine.   Doctor recommended that she be seen by her PCP as she has not improved.  1/14: called and went to her PCP as advised by Doctor.  now has a UTI and URI.  She is on Macrobid and Levoquin as well as Zofran and Phenergan.  Her BP was 117/60 and dehydrated.    Her PCP told her to monitor her BP and return to ER if not improved and also return to ER if symptoms became worse. will call on Monday 1/18/2020 and update us on her condition  1/17:COVID tests were negative, over 48 hours since a temp above 100.4, 99.1 was the last temp doing better. No more vomiting and no diarrhea. still has a cough and is still on ABX from all of her symptoms. Is on a cough suppressant so recommend her working from home since she is able and will update us towards the end of the week on how she is doing.  1/20: Received the COVID vaccine on 1/5/21.  Released  yesterday to work from home.  No longer has vomiting or diarrhea.  COVID, FLU and strep tests negative.  Diagnosed with allergic reaction to COVID Vaccine. had kidney infection and UTI.  CT of abdomen done with contrast.  CXR to r/o pneumonia.  continues to have a runny nose, no fever.   Continues to have laryngitis and fatigue. called today to get released.  Encouraged to call back when she gains more strength and can return.  My PCP diagnosed me with a severe allergic reaction to the covid shot. I had the rapid covid test ran twice and the  test sent out twice, all 4 tests came back negative. I had the flu test ran and it came back negative. So did the strep culture. I had 2 full lab workups ran and they both came back normal including my vitamin levels. The only thing that was out of alinement was my white cell count was high due to an infection.    Today, I am currently running a fever of 99.4. I still have a cough that is rather irritating. I still do not have a voice. I am retaining color back in my skin. I am still tired and weak but have managed to work and do small things around the house such as cook dinner, wash laundry, clean dishes, and shower. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received at 12:15pm. Other than a slightly sore arm nothing until 6pm.  Started at 6pm with the injection site being very warm and the whole right arm began to heat and swell all joints from knuckles to my neck began aching at a 7 on a 1-10 pain scale. At 6pm the rest of the joints in my body began aching but not as bad as the injection arm. By 10pm I was extremely nauseous and had a steady throbbing headache and was only able to sit as any movement was painful and nauseating. I vomited twice that night. By 6am the next day I was unable to grip or lift anything with the injection arm as moving it all caused intense pressure and pain in that arm a 8.5-9 on the 1-10 scale. By this time my entire body was a steady and constant 8 pain wise. Especially my lower back and hips my joints felt like they were being crushed and pulled apart.  I was unable to get out of bed except 3 times to pee for the entire second day. The pain in the lower back, hips and injection arm increased to the point where I would just cry and yell as it was the worst joint and back pain I have ever had in my life. I tried sleeping most of the day and would wake from the pain.  I have not had a period in about 4 years and had vaginal bleeding like a period that night with abdominal cramping as well. There was nothing that relieved the pain but time. By 10pm the pain finally subsided some and today 1/24 two days post injection the pain is now a constant dull joint ache like a normal flu ache. I am still very sore in the injection arm but can move it today, still causes too much pain and pressure to lift or pull with it. If I sit or stand up for more than 30 minutes my arm begins to throb and the headache and nausea come back.
LAB_DATA: None as I have no healthcare or doctor.
